<dl id="n05132d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05132d">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05132d"> 132(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> lingua muta (bestioni) / (T &amp; I)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Vico holds that language was earlier pure poetry and was originally a speechless language]</font> In cotal guisa della Lingua muta de? bestioni di Obbes, semplicioni di Grozio, solitarj di Pufendorfio incominciati a venire all&apos;Umanit&agrave;, cominciossi tratto tratto a formare la Lingua di ciascheduna antica nazione, prima delle volgari presenti, Poetica &hellip; <font color="green">[In this way, from the mute languages of the great beasts of Hobbes, Grotius&apos;s simpletons, and the solitary beings of Pudendorf, once they had come into humanity, the poetic languages of the ancient nations came gradually to be formed at a time before our present vulgar languages arose.]</font> <small> Giambattista Vico, <a name="VICO" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#VICO"><cite title="source">Principj di una Scienza Nuova</cite></a> (1836) III, Ch. XXV</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
